15 First Amendment to the United States Constitution and in Paragraphs III and IV of
16 Section I, Article I of the Constitution of this state, respectively;
17 (2) Whereas in City of Boerne v. Flores, 521 U.S. 507 (1997), the United States Supreme
18 Court held that the compelling interest test provided for in the federal Religious Freedom
19 Restoration Act, to protect the inalienable constitutional right of free exercise of religion,
20 must be adopted by a state through legislative act or court decision in order to apply to
21 state or local government action; and
22 (3) The General Assembly has determined that the following legislative act adopts the
23 same compelling interest test provided for in the federal Religious Freedom Restoration
24 Act in a manner that applies it to the actions of state and local governments in Georgia.
25 SECTION 3.
26 Title 50 of the Official Code of Georgia Annotated, relating to state government, is amended
27 by adding a new chapter to read as follows:
28 "CHAPTER 15A
29 50-15A-1.
30 (a) Government shall not substantially burden a person's exercise of religion even if the
31 burden results from a rule of general applicability, except as provided in subsection (b) of
32 this Code section.
33 (b) Government may substantially burden a person's exercise of religion only if it
34 demonstrates that application of the burden to the person is:
35 (1) In furtherance of a compelling governmental interest; and
36 (2) The least restrictive means of furthering such compelling governmental interest.
